  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    An architectural pattern is a&amp;nbsp;reusable solution to a commonly occurring problem. Each pattern applies to&#xD;
    a&amp;nbsp;defined context.&amp;nbsp;In the context of IT architectural as defined by UAM, architecture patterns may be applied&#xD;
    to a perspective or to a set of aspects. Patterns may also be specific to a level, the Business, Logical or Technical&#xD;
    levels.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_UAM__patterns&quot; name=&quot;XE_UAM__patterns&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Architecture_patterns&quot;&#xD;
name=&quot;XE_Architecture_patterns&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Architectural patterns are similar to design patterns, but since the context is IT architecture the focus is more on&#xD;
    form (structure) rather than detailed design specifications (and functions). An architectural pattern is defined as “an&#xD;
    idea that has been useful in one practical context and will probably be useful in others” &lt;a&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../UAM/guidances/supportingmaterials/uam_references_229FFDF2.html&quot; guid=&quot;_nQFYAMb-EeK4P8KZ6MNYcg&quot;>(Fowler&#xD;
    1997)&lt;/a>. UAM defines architectural patterns as “a generic form and set of functions that defines an approach to&#xD;
    solving a problem”. Architectural patterns focus on the form of the solution. Note that in the UAM context the scope&#xD;
    includes hardware, software, and other aspects of the IT architecture, not just software. Therefore, the patterns of&#xD;
    use need to cover this wider scope and include software, hardware, and even location patterns.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Each patterns is defined using the following structure:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Introduction&lt;/strong> – a brief introduction to the pattern;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Name&lt;/strong> – a meaningful name conveying its context and purpose;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Problem&lt;/strong> – the problem that the pattern solves is described;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Context&lt;/strong> – conditions or situation where the pattern is applicable;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Constraints&lt;/strong> – issues or constraints relative to the context. The description clarifies the problem&#xD;
        and any issues that must be considered. Aspects considered under constraints include: &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Security, availability, reliability, fault-tolerance;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Manageability and maintainability;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Performance, and other non-functional aspects;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Scalability, modularity, completeness;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Ease of implementation;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Ease of use.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Solution&lt;/strong> – a description of the pattern using text and graphics. It should include both the static&#xD;
        structure and its dynamic behavior if applicable. Guidelines for implementing the solution may also be included&#xD;
        along with any variants or specializations. An explanation of the pattern and its rationale should be included—how&#xD;
        the pattern actually works and why it should be used;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Related Patterns&lt;/strong> – relationships with other patterns are described. These may be predecessor&#xD;
        patterns, successor patterns, alternative patterns, or co-dependent patterns.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
